The paper deals with the mitigation of intersymbol interference in a diffusive molecular communication system, which involves the transmission of information molecules through a propagation environment. This is a topic that falls under the intersection of several CS sub-disciplines, including information theory (cs.IT), neural networks (cs.NE), control systems (cs.SY), multimedia (cs.MM), and bioinformatics (cs.BIO). Given the focus on communication performance and the use of enzymes to improve receiver performance, cs.IT and cs.NE are the most likely sub-categories. However, the paper also discusses the selection of an appropriate bit interval and the expected bit error probability, which are topics that fall under cs.SY and cs.MM. Finally, the use of enzymes in molecular communication is a topic that is specific to cs.BIO.
